## ðŸ” **Critical Architecture Pattern**

### **CLIENT ACTIONS vs SERVER ACTIONS**

This is a **CRITICAL DISTINCTION** that affects authentication and Firestore security rules.

#### âœ… **CLIENT ACTIONS** (`src/lib/client-actions.ts`)
**When to Use:**
- Creating surveys
- Updating surveys
- Deleting surveys
- ANY operation requiring admin authentication
- ANY write operation protected by Firestore security rules

**Why:**
```typescript
// CLIENT ACTIONS run in the BROWSER
// âœ… Has Firebase Auth context (user is authenticated)
// âœ… Firestore rules can check request.auth.token.email
// âœ… Admin verification works: isAdmin() checks request.auth
```

**Import Pattern:**
```typescript
// âœ… CORRECT for components
import { createSurvey, updateSurvey, deleteSurvey } from '@/lib/client-actions';
```

#### âŒ **SERVER ACTIONS** (`src/app/*/actions.ts`)
**When to Use:**
- Read operations (listSurveys, getSurvey)
- Operations that don't require authentication
- Server-side rendering data fetching
- Operations using Firebase Admin SDK (when implemented)

**Why:**
```typescript
// SERVER ACTIONS run on the SERVER
// âŒ NO Firebase Auth context (request.auth is null)
// âŒ Firestore rules CANNOT check request.auth.token.email
// âŒ Admin verification FAILS: isAdmin() returns false
```

**Import Pattern:**
```typescript
// âœ… CORRECT for server-side data fetching
import { listSurveys, getSurvey } from '@/app/editor/actions';

// âŒ WRONG for authenticated writes
import { createSurvey, updateSurvey } from '@/app/editor/actions'; // PERMISSION DENIED!
```

